      <div class="subtext">
          <h1>Stationary</h1>
          <h3>November 2021 - December 2021</h3><br>
          <p class="top">Created in Unity, Stationary is one of the more atmospheric games I've had the chance to work on. With only a month to develop, I was largely responsible for the production managment of this game. Stationary follows a security guard trapped in an endlees loop of rooms as a black mold slowly eats away at the world. I needed to find a way to design a moody experience to fit the gritty artwork and ominous story provided by my group members. All the while, I had to set weekly deadlines and schedule meetings to maintain a production timeline. I also scripted the object interactions to craft the puzzle required to escape the loop.</p>
          <p><a href="https://juicecube.itch.io/stationary"class="viewLink">Click Here to Play Stationary</a></p>
      </div>
      <div class="subimg">
          <img src="/assets/img/onwardPrince.png" alt="Screenshot from Onward Wanderer!">
      </div>
      <div class="subtext">
          <h1>Onward Wanderer!</h1>
          <h3>May 2022</h3><br>
          <p class="top">One weekend in May 2022, I decided to finally decided to sit down and put my gathered knowledge of Unreal Engine 4 to the test. Onward Wanderer was a self-imposed challenge to develop a game to apply my knowledge of level design to the test. My main goal was to curate an open level environment with an emphasis on verticality and climbing with minimal explicit direction. I also had a high focus on making sure to properly pace out high energy combat sections with low energy exploration areas. Onwards and Upwards! Oh wait... That would have been a much better name for the game in hindsight.</p>
        </div>
      <div class="subimg">
          <img src="/assets/img/shiftingTalismans.png" alt="Screenshot from Shifting Talismans">
      </div>
      <div class="subtext">
          <h1>Shifting Talismans</h1>
          <h3>October 2021</h3><br>
          <p class="top">Shifting Talismans is a relatively simple tile-matching game I developed with a small team in Unity. The object of the game is to drag rows and columns of colored blocks to get each block in it's correct position. My role in this project was to develop the art, assets, and animation for this project. It was an incredibly fun experience to draw and animate the countless demons that represented the time limit in each level.</p>
          <p><a href="https://juicecube.itch.io/shifting-talismans"class="viewLink">Click Here to Play Shifting Talismans</a></p>
        </div>
      <div class="subimg">
          <img src="/assets/img/haunting.png" alt="Screenshot from The Haunting of the Lone Cabin">
      </div>
      <div class="subtext">
          <h1>The Haunting of the Lone Cabin</h1>
          <h3>November 2020 - December 2020</h3><br>
          <p class="top">Why yes, I model too! Pictured to the left is a screenshot from my game The Haunting of the Lone Cabin. It's a simple world meant to serve as a gallery for a 3D Modeling and Animation course I took at RIT. The project was a group effort between me and a few of my peers, however I will specify that I modeled, textured, and imported to Unity all models that you can see within the screenshot. Prior to taking this course I had no experience with 3D animation, but after working in Maya and growing to understand how to model, UV unwrap, texture, rig, and animate I've grown really fond of the process!</p>
      </div>
      <div class="subimg">
